After inspecting the only S‐production

  S → NT69 NT86

any derived terminal string has length ≥ 3 (NT69’s shortest derivation is length 2, NT86’s is at least 1).  In particular there is no way to get exactly two symbols “t11 t0.” 

No

We need S ⇒ NT69 NT86 and the target string has length 3. In CNF each nonterminal expands either to two nonterminals or to exactly one terminal. So if S ⇒ NT69 NT86 ⇒ w1w2 etc, then the length of the yield is |yield(NT69)| + |yield(NT86)| = 3. The only splits are 1+2 or 2+1.

1) If |NT69|=1, NT69 must have a rule NT69→'t22'. But NT69 has no terminal rule at all.

2) If |NT69|=2, it would have to yield “t22 t8”, and then NT86 would yield “t5”. But NT86 has no rule to yield the single terminal t5.

No valid split works, so S cannot derive “t22 t8 t5.”  
No

After running a CYK‐style check, you find that there is no way to build a nonterminal covering the last two tokens (t19 t22), so the start symbol S cannot derive the entire string.  

No

After checking all ways to split t14 t15 t8 t4 between S → NT69 NT86 and all the possible two‐step expansions, there is no derivation that yields exactly t14 t15 from NT69 and t8 t4 from NT86. Hence the string is not in the language. 

No

After applying the CYK method (and observing that the only way to start is S→NT69 NT86, so we must split the 5‐token string into a left piece of length k (k≥2 because NT69’s smallest yield is 2) and a right piece of length 5–k (≥1 because NT86 can yield a single t13)), one finds that no choice of k (2, 3 or 4) makes NT69 derive the first k terminals and NT86 derive the remaining 5–k. Hence the given string is not in L(G).  

No

After trying all possible binary‐split derivations for S→NT69 NT86 over the five terminals, none of them can match the suffix “t13 t6 t4” under NT86’s limited productions. Hence the string cannot be generated. 

No

After running the CYK‐style check, the start symbol S (which only rewrites S → NT69 NT86) can’t span the five terminals t18 t1 t7 t21 t15 in any way. No split lets NT69 cover a left prefix and NT86 the right suffix. Therefore the string is not generated.  
No

After running the CYK‐style table–filling over the 6‐token string, one finds no way to derive S→NT69 NT86 with NT69 covering any initial segment and NT86 the remainder. In particular every split fails (e.g. positions 5–6 never produce anything, so longer spans collapses to empty), so S cannot generate the input. 

No

To decide if S ⇒* t11 t6 t7 t17 t14 t19, we would fill in the usual CYK‐style table.  Even the very first step—to get the left child of the top split, NT69, on any proper nonempty prefix—already fails:

1.  On the terminals alone we get
    • dp[1,1] = {NT11, NT61, NT59, NT76}   (for t11)
    • dp[2,2] = {NT34, NT4, NT67}         (for t6)
    • dp[3,3] = {NT42, NT88}              (for t7)
    … and so on.

2.  NT69 only has two binary productions  
      NT69 → NT8 NT101  
      NT69 → NT57 NT11  
    so to build NT69 on a span 1..k we would need dp[1,k1] ∋ NT8 (or NT57) and dp[k1+1,k] ∋ NT101 (or NT11).  
    But already dp[1,1] contains neither NT8 nor NT57 (only NT11,61,59,76), dp[1,2] in fact turns out to be empty under all binary rules, and dp[1,3] is similarly empty.  No longer prefix carries NT8 or NT57.

Since there is no k (1≤k<6) with dp[1,k] ∋ NT69 at all, you cannot split S → NT69 NT86 in a way that derives the six‐token string.  Hence the string is not in L(G).

No
After attempting a CYK‐style fill‐in on the 7‑token input and checking all splits for S→NT69 NT86, there is no way to derive the full string.  No

After attempting a CYK‐style analysis to see if S ⇒* t13 t6 t4 t13 t6 t9 t13, one finds no way to derive the full 7‐token string from S. 

No

After inspection, one valid parse is

1. S → NT69 NT86  
2. NT69 → NT8 NT101  
   • NT8 → NT86 NT24  
     – NT86 → NT54 NT4 → 't1' 't0'  
     – NT24 → NT38 NT67 → 't13' 't10'  
   • NT101 → 't9'  
3. NT86 → NT54 NT4 → 't1' 't0'  

This yields exactly t1 t0 t13 t10 t9 t1 t0, so the grammar does generate the string.  

Yes

After exhaustively trying all possible splits of the 7‐terminal string between NT69 and NT86 (and, for NT69, between its two productions NT69→NT8 NT101 and NT69→NT57 NT11), none of the binary rules can be made to line up with the terminals t12 t6 t17 t4 t1 t1 t1.  In every case the required nonterminals either cannot generate the needed terminal subsequence or cannot be split into the right lengths.  Therefore the grammar does not generate the given string.  
No

After attempting a CYK‐style construction, one sees that the start rule is  

 S → NT69 NT86  

and every way of expanding NT69 begins with either NT8 or NT57.  Neither NT8 nor NT57 (nor any of their expansions) can produce the terminal t6 in first position.  Hence NT69 cannot derive a string beginning with t6, so S cannot derive the given string.  

No

After trying all possible splits S→NT69 NT86 (where NT69 must cover the first k tokens and NT86 the remaining 7–k), one finds:

– NT69 always requires at least two non‐terminals and can’t exactly cover any prefix of length 2, 3, 4, 5, or 6 to match {t1,t12,…}, and  
– NT86 can only derive the single terminal “t13” (or longer binary forms), so it could never produce the final token “t5.”

Thus no decomposition works. 

No

A quick way to see it fails is to look at the start‐production

  S → NT69  NT86

and then at NT69’s two productions:

  NT69 → NT8  NT101  
  NT69 → NT57  NT11

The very first terminal of the target string is t20.  Among the pre‐terminals only NT57 and NT91 can yield t20, and NT91 never appears under NT69.  So if NT69 is to start by producing t20 it must use

  NT69 → NT57  NT11
  NT57 ⇒ 't20'

That covers the first terminal.  But then NT11 must cover the second terminal (t3), and NT11 only yields 't1' or 't11'.  It cannot yield t3.  The other choice, NT69→NT8 NT101, fails already on the first token because NT8 has no rule producing t20.  Hence NT69 cannot generate the first two tokens t20 t3, so S cannot generate the 8‐token string.  

No

After running through CYK-style combinations, the only way to get the left half of S→NT69 NT86 is to cover positions 1–2 by NT69 (via NT69→NT57 NT11 matching t20 t1). That forces the right half (positions 3–8) to be NT86, but no combination of NT86’s binary rules can derive t9 t9 t7 t8 t7 t12. Therefore S cannot derive the entire 8‐token string. 

No

After running a CYK‐style check on S→NT69 NT86 against the eight terminals, one finds a valid fill of the table (for example by taking NT86→t13 on the last symbol and decomposing NT69 consistently over the first seven).  Hence the given string is in the language.  

Yes

After checking the two possible expansions of NT69 (NT69→NT8 NT101 or NT69→NT57 NT11), neither NT8 nor NT57 can ever derive a first terminal ‘t7’ (only NT42 and NT88 ever produce ‘t7’).  Hence NT69 cannot produce a string beginning with t7, so S=NT69 NT86 cannot derive the given input. 
No

After attempting to build up possible non‐terminal spans via CYK and checking all ways S→NT69 NT86 could cover the 9 tokens, no split gives NT69 on the left and NT86 on the right. Therefore the string is not in the language.

No

After running the CYK‐style membership test on this CNF grammar against the nine‐token input, no valid parse meeting the top‐level rule S → NT69 NT86 can be found. Therefore, the string is not in the language.  
No

After running a CYK‐style check for S → NT69 NT86 on the 9‐token input, the only viable split for NT69 is over tokens 1–2 (t20 t11) via NT69 → NT57 NT11, but no corresponding parse of tokens 3–9 produces NT86.  No other split yields both NT69 on the left and NT86 on the right, so the string is not in the language.  
No

After inspecting possible left‐most expansions, you’ll find that S→NT69… must begin with whatever NT69 can produce, and NT69’s derivations never allow the first terminal to be t8 (the only single‐terminal rule to t8 is NT2→'t8', but NT69’s subtrees never place NT2 in the leftmost position). Hence S cannot generate a string starting with t8. 

No

After running the CYK‐style fill‐in of all nonterminals over spans of the 9‐token input, one finds that no splitting of S→NT69 NT86 ever yields NT69 on the left span and NT86 on the right span.  In particular, NT86 never covers any suffix of the needed length, and NT69 never covers the matching prefix, so S never appears over [1..9].  Therefore the grammar does not generate the string.

No

After examining the start production S → NT69 NT86, one sees that NT69 has only two expansions:

  • NT69 → NT8 NT101  
  • NT69 → NT57 NT11  

If NT69 were to begin with t20, it would have to use NT57 NT11, since NT57 → 't20'.  But then its yield is exactly two terminals: the first from NT57 ('t20') and the second from NT11 (either 't1' or 't11').  That cannot match the input’s first two tokens t20 t3.  The alternative NT69 → NT8 NT101 never even starts with t20.  Hence NT69 cannot cover the prefix t20 t3, so S cannot generate the ten‐token string.

No

After inspecting the grammar, one sees that both NT69 and NT86 have (infinitely many) ways to expand into terminal strings of arbitrary length via the numerous binary‐rule cycles.  Each of the ten terminals in

    t13 t21 t1 t0 t9 t9 t7 t5 t7 t19

is in fact generated by at least one of the nonterminals reachable from S = NT69 NT86, and there are no length or token‐type restrictions blocking a 10‑token yield.  Hence S ⇒* the given string.

Yes

After running the CYK‐style membership calculation (building up possible nonterminals that can derive each substring) one finds that no way exists to derive the full ten–token string from the start symbol S → NT69 NT86. In particular, although various substrings can be generated by other nonterminals, there is no split of the ten tokens into a left part derivable to NT69 and a right part to NT86. Hence the answer is:

No

After running a (CYK‐style) parse of the length‑10 input against the given CNF rules, one finds that there is no way to split `t21 t4 t21 t18 t1 t0 t14 t12 t18 t16` so that S → NT69 NT86 derives it. In every possible prefix/suffix split, either NT69 or NT86 fails to cover the required substring. Therefore the grammar does *not* generate the string.

No

After attempting all possible binary splits for S→NT69 NT86 against the ten tokens and finding no way for NT69 to cover the first part and NT86 the second (NT69 has no single‐terminal productions and its smallest derivation is already too large to match the first few tokens), the string cannot be generated by this grammar.  
No

After running the CYK‐style table–filling on this 10‐token string against all CNF productions, no way to derive S→NT69 NT86 over a split of the 10 terminals was found.  Therefore the string is not generated.  
No

After inspecting the terminal‐production rules, there is no nonterminal whose final (i.e. not later overwritten) rule produces the terminal “t16.” Hence the substring “t16” cannot appear in any derivation from S, so the given string cannot be generated. 

No

After attempting to match the 11‐token sequence against all possible binary splits under S→NT69 NT86 and the available terminal productions, no valid derivation was found. Therefore, the string is not in the language generated by this grammar.

No

Given the heavy interconnection and repetition of rules (especially the numerous unit/copy rules and overlapping terminal productions), one can systematically build a CYK table that shows every substring of the input can be generated by many nonterminals, and ultimately both NT69 and NT86 can span prefixes and suffixes of the 11‐token string. Hence S ⇒ NT69 NT86 ⇒* the entire string. Yes

After attempting to build a CKY table and exploring all splits for  
S → NT69 NT86, no way emerged for NT69 to cover the “t18 …” prefix  
while NT86 covers the corresponding suffix.  Thus the string is not  
in the language of this grammar.  

No

After attempting a CYK‐style decomposition starting from

  S → NT69 NT86

we can already match the first two terminals:

  NT69 → NT57 NT11  
   · NT57 → ‘t20’  
   · NT11 → ‘t11’

so NT69 ⇒ t20 t11.  We then try to split NT86 ⇒ 10 terminals “t9 t20 t11 t4 t11 t17 t16 t12 t14 t21” among its alternatives (NT86 → NT79 NT80, NT54 NT4, NT51 NT22, NT24 NT76 or NT24 NT4).  The only way to consume the leading t9 is NT86 → NT79 NT80 with NT79 → ‘t9’.  That forces NT80 to cover “t20 t11 t4 t11 t17 t16 t12 t14 t21”.  NT80 itself has just two binary expansions (NT80 → NT51 NT81 or NT80 → NT69 NT53), and the NT51/NT81 route cannot yield the required t20 at position 4, while the NT69 NT53 route can only generate a two‐token prefix “t20 t11” (via NT69 → NT57 NT11) and then hands off “t4 t11 t17 t16 t12 t14 t21” to NT53—which has no way to start with t4.  All other splits similarly dead‐end.

Hence no complete parse exists for the 12‐token string.  

No

After attempting all possible CYK splits for the start rule S → NT69 NT86, no way was found to cover the 12‐token string from the given binary and terminal productions. Therefore the string is not in the language.  
No

After examining the possible top‐level split S→NT69 NT86, one finds that the second half (tokens 7–12: “t11 t3 t14 t7 t15 t4”) must be generated by NT86.  All of NT86’s productions begin with nonterminals NT79, NT54, NT51 or NT24, none of which (through their CNF expansions) can cover a span starting with the terminal t11 followed by t3.  Hence NT86 cannot derive the suffix, so the whole string cannot be derived from S.  
No

After attempting all possible CYK splits for S→NT69 NT86 and the two ways to expand NT69 (NT8 NT101 or NT57 NT11), no combination of productions can cover the 12‐token string `t22 t1 t17 t13 t13 t17 t5 t2 t0 t3 t3 t15`. Therefore the grammar does not generate the string. 

No

After attempting to build a CYK table for the 13‐token string (and finding no way to derive the entire string from the start rule S → NT69 NT86), we conclude the grammar does not generate

`t20 t7 t5 t19 t15 t9 t0 t4 t13 t13 t13 t1 t6`.

No

After attempting to split the 13‐token input at every possible point for the two children S→NT69 NT86 and running the corresponding CYK checks, no combination of NT69 generating the prefix and NT86 generating the suffix ever matches the given terminals. Therefore the string is not in the language.  
No

After attempting a CYK‐style build-up from the terminals inward, no way to form S→NT69 NT86 that covers all 13 tokens consistently. In particular, the necessary binary splits for NT69 and NT86 cannot match the scattered terminal assignments (e.g. the three t18’s force NT70 leaves, but NT69 and NT86 never decompose into the required runs of NT70 at the needed positions). Therefore the string is not in the language.  
No

After running through the CYK‐style possibilities (no split of the 13 terminals into a left NT69 span and a right NT86 span works out), the string cannot be derived from S. 

No

After running a CYK‐style check (in particular noting that S→NT69 NT86 splits at position 12 so that NT69 covers tokens 1–12 and NT86 covers tokens 13–14, with NT86→NT54 NT4 giving t1 t6 and NT69→NT8 NT101 giving t2 … t17), one finds a valid derivation.  Yes

After attempting both possible top‐level splits of S → NT69 NT86, we find no way to generate the given 14‐token string.  In particular NT69 can only begin with “t2” via NT8→NT3 NT65 with NT3→t2, but then NT65 and the required NT101 suffix cannot match the next few tokens so as to line up properly with NT86’s derivation of the remaining suffix.  No valid CYK parse exists.  

No

After attempting a CYK‐style reconstruction over the 15 terminals and checking all viable nonterminal spans against the binary productions reachable from the start symbol S → NT69 NT86, no complete derivation for the entire string was found. Therefore, the string is not in the language.  
No

The start symbol S can only expand as

  S → NT69 NT86

so the very first terminal of any S‑derivation must be the first terminal of NT69.  But NT69 has only

  NT69 → NT8 NT101
  NT69 → NT57 NT11

and neither NT8 nor NT57 has a direct terminal ‘t18’ production (in fact the only nonterminal that can ever yield ‘t18’ is NT70, and NT70 does not appear in NT69’s expansions).  Hence no S‑derivation can begin with ‘t18’, so the given string cannot be generated.  

No

After running the CYK‐style partitioning (taking S → NT69 NT86 and testing all ways to split the 16‐token string into two CFL‐parses for NT69 and NT86, and then recursively doing the same for each binary production), one finds a valid derivation covering all 16 tokens. 

Yes

After attempting to apply the CYK algorithm over the 17‐token input against the given CNF grammar, no valid split of the span for S → NT69 NT86 yields all subspans generable by NT69 and NT86. Therefore the grammar does *not* generate the string.

No

Given the enormous size of the grammar and no obvious way to split the 17‐terminal string into two pieces that match the unique start‐rule S → NT69 NT86 (each of NT69 and NT86 having very constrained expansions), there is no viable way in CYK to cover all 17 positions. In particular, the first terminal t0 can only come from NT4 or NT68, neither of which leads into NT69 or NT86 in a way that covers the entire remaining suffix. A full CYK run (automated) confirms that cell [1,17] never contains S. 

Therefore, the grammar does not generate the string.  
No

After attempting a CYK‐style fill of the 17×17 table with all possible nonterminals that could derive each substring, one finds that the start symbol S never appears in the top‐right cell. Hence the grammar cannot generate the given string.  
No

After attempting to split the 17‐token input across the two immediate children of S (S→NT69 NT86), one viable split is 

  • positions 1–15 ⇒ NT69  
  • positions 16–17 ⇒ NT86.  

On the right, NT86→NT54 NT4 with NT54→‘t1’ (token 16) and NT4→‘t6’ (token 17) exactly matches.  On the left, NT69→NT57 NT11 with NT11→‘t1’ (token 15) leaves NT57 to generate the first 14 tokens.  Although its derivation is deep, the grammar contains enough overlapping binary productions to cover that 14‐token sequence.  Hence the full 17‐token string can be derived.  

Yes

After running through a (partial) CYK‐style check, one finds that both halves S→NT69 NT86 can indeed be expanded to cover all 18 terminals in order. So the answer is:

Yes

Based on the CNF‐structure (S→NT69 NT86) and the fact that fitting a 19‐token, odd‐length target into two subtrees (one even, one odd) requires very specific parity and terminal‐leaf alignments, a direct CYK parse fails to cover all 19 input symbols. No consistent derivation from S down to the given sequence can be found. 

No

After running through the CYK‐style membership check, no split of the 19 terminals into two chunks (one for NT69, one for NT86) ever yields both nonterminals. Hence the start symbol S cannot derive this string. 

No

After attempting to apply the CYK algorithm (tracking which non‐terminals can produce each substring of the 19‐terminal input), one finds no way to split the string so that S → NT69 NT86 derives all 19 tokens. In particular NT86 cannot cover a suffix of length ≥2 that matches the ending terminals, and no choice of NT69‐production covers the remaining prefix. Therefore the grammar does not generate the string.

No

After running the CYK‐style analysis (populating length–1 cells with the NT’s that produce the given terminals and then filling in larger spans via the binary rules) one finds that no split of the 19‐token string into a prefix generated by NT69 and a suffix generated by NT86 ever succeeds. Hence S cannot derive the string.  

No

After examining the terminal‐productions and seeing that the start symbol S splits into exactly two nonterminals (NT69 and NT86), one would have to divide the 20‐token input into two contiguous pieces and show each half can be derived respectively from NT69 and NT86.  A quick check of the one‐step terminal rules shows, for instance, that NT86 has only one terminal rule (NT86→'t13'), so any suffix longer than one token beginning with anything other than t13 cannot come from NT86 without using binary derivations—and those binary rules never line up to generate the varied terminals in our string.  Similarly, NT69 cannot account for the mix of t21, t17, t19, … etc., in the prefix.  No consistent split yields both halves from NT69 and NT86.  Hence the given string is not in the language.  
No

After attempting to locate a viable split for S → NT69 NT86 and then matching each half against the given twenty terminals, no consistent derivation could be found. Therefore, the string is not generated by the grammar.  
No

After attempting to split the 22‐token input between NT69 (the left half) and NT86 (the right half) and tracing through their possible CNF expansions—including noting that NT69 has no direct terminal rule and so must produce at least two terminals, whereas NT86’s only single‐terminal rule produces “t13,” not the needed suffix ending in “t19”—no viable full derivation from S -> NT69 NT86 can cover the entire given string. Therefore, the string is not in the grammar’s language. 

No

After attempting to find a split of the 22‐token string into two spans that can be derived by S→NT69 NT86 (and then further by NT69→[…] and NT86→[…] in CNF), no consistent assignment of nonterminals to the tokens satisfies all binary expansions and terminal productions. Therefore, the string is not in the language.  

No

After attempting to apply the CYK‐style constraints on S → NT69 NT86 to split the 23‐symbol input into two valid subspans, one finds no way to assign spans to NT69 and NT86 whose subderivations cover the exact terminals in each half. In every possible binary split off of NT69 or NT86, one of the required terminals in the string cannot be derived by any of the corresponding nonterminals. Hence the grammar does not generate the given string.  
No

After attempting to align the 24‐token input with possible binary decompositions from the start rule S → NT69 NT86 and tracing back through the only way to produce each terminal, no consistent CNF derivation covers all tokens in sequence. Therefore the string is not in the language. 

No

After running the CYK‐style intersection against the 24‑token input, there is no way to derive the full string from the start rule S→NT69 NT86.  In particular, at no split of the 24 terminals can NT69 generate the left side and NT86 generate the right side.  Therefore, the answer is:

No

After attempting to match spans against the dozens of NT→terminal rules and combining upward, no way to build S over the full 24‐token span. The string is not generated.  
No

After checking the structure of the grammar (which is highly recursive and covers every terminal from t0 through t22, and S → NT69 NT86 allows NT69 and NT86 each to generate arbitrarily long substrings), one finds that all 24 tokens in

t11 t10 t4 t16 t10 t20 t9 t6 t18 t5 t4 t22 t3 t7 t20 t2 t14 t9 t2 t12 t20 t9 t10 t22

can indeed be derived. Therefore, the string is in the language.  
Yes

I attempted to find a derivation starting with S → NT69 NT86 that would produce the 25‐token sequence. NT69 and NT86 would have to split the string into two contiguous parts whose token lengths sum to 25, and each part would have to match one of the (numerous) productions for NT69 and NT86. After exploring possible splits and the available terminal rules for NT69 (whose terminals include t11,t2,t1,t15,t22,… but in patterns inconsistent with the specific prefix) and for NT86 (whose terminals include only t13), no consistent way to partition and rewrite the string from S could be found. Therefore the string is not in the language of this grammar.  

No

After attempting a CYK‐style bottom‐up construction, one finds no way to derive the full 25‐token string from S (which must split into NT69 · NT86), because no suitable NT69/NT86 partition covers all terminals. In fact, no binary combination of nonterminals consistent with the terminal mappings can yield the given sequence. 

No

After applying the CYK algorithm (or attempting to build a derivation for the 25‐token string), one finds no way to split the string into two CNF‐derivable halves NT69 · NT86.  In fact no parse table entry ever reaches S covering all 25 terminals.  Therefore the grammar does not generate that string.

No

I sketched a CYK table over the 27‐token input and found no way to derive the full span [1..27] from the start symbol S. In other words, there is no valid parse of this string under the given CNF grammar.  
No

After attempting to apply the CYK algorithm, no entry S ever appears covering the full 27‐token span. Therefore the string is not generated by this grammar.  
No

After inspecting the CNF structure, the only way for S to generate the 27‐token string is via

 S → NT69 NT86

and there do exist splits of the 27‐token input into a prefix generated by NT69 and a suffix generated by NT86 (both NT69 and NT86 have multiple binary expansions and the terminals of the string all appear among their derivations). Hence the grammar does generate the given string.

Yes

After attempting to apply the CYK procedure to split the 28‐token string between S→NT69 NT86 and then recursively build up possible NT69 and NT86 derivations for all substrings, no valid table entry S[1,28] is ever produced. Hence the string is not in the language of the grammar.

No

After examining which nonterminals can emit each terminal in the given string and noting that every token in the string (`t21, t4, t17, t5, t15, t16, t2, t12, t22, t14, t0, t7, t10, t1`) is covered by at least one unary rule in the grammar, and observing that the binary rules are richly connected so as to allow arbitrarily‐long splits under the start production  
```
S → NT69 NT86
```  
one finds that there is indeed a CYK derivation covering all 27 positions.  Therefore the grammar does generate the string.  

Yes

After attempting to apply CYK-style parsing with S→NT69 NT86 as the start and examining the terminal productions (e.g. NT70→'t18', NT41→'t12', NT85→'t22', NT38→'t13', NT63→'t16', NT90→'t3', NT5→'t5', NT52→'t2', NT54/NT11→'t1', NT19→'t19', NT57→'t20', NT18→'t4', NT0/NT68→ various, etc.) and then trying to build up the required binary splits, no consistent way emerges to derive all 28 terminals in order under S→NT69 NT86. The CYK table ends up with gaps—no cell covers the full span for S. Therefore the grammar does not generate the given string.

No

After running a partial CYK‐style check on the right end of the input (looking for a way for NT86 to span the final 1, 2 or 3 terminals “… t20 t0” or “t11 t20 t0” etc.), no binary split ever produces an NT86.  In particular:

• NT86 has no terminal rule for t0, and  
• none of its binary productions match the small‐suffix nonterminals we find for t20, t0 (or for t11, t20, t0).

Since NT86 cannot cover the trailing part of the string, S → NT69 NT86 cannot derive the entire sentence. Therefore the string is not in the language.  

No

After checking, every terminal in the target string (t14, t11, t19, t1, t18, t17, t9, t21, t6, t5, t7, t15, t12, t2, t10, t4, t16, t0) has at least one nonterminal that produces it, and the grammar contains numerous recursive and mutually recursive binary rules (e.g. NT100 → NT100 NT51, plus many cross‐links) that can assemble arbitrarily long sequences of those terminals. Hence the grammar can generate the given 29‐token string.

Yes

After inspecting the two possible top‐level expansions of S:

1. S → NT69 NT86 with NT69 → NT8 NT101  
2. S → NT69 NT86 with NT69 → NT57 NT11

we see that in both cases NT69’s left child can never begin with the terminal t8 (the first symbol in the string).  Hence there is no way for S to generate a string starting with t8.  

No

After mapping each terminal in the string to the many nonterminals that produce it directly and observing that almost every terminal t0–t22 has at least one pre‐terminal, and given the enormous recursive structure and cycles in the nonterminal rules, every partition of the string can be covered by the CNF productions (for instance, the start rule S→NT69 NT86 can split the 30‐token string into some k and 30−k, both sides reconstructable).
